ce:section.ce:para:
For the purposes of this scientometric investigation, we employed the Science Citation Index Expanded (SCIE), part of the Web of Science Core Collection (WoSCC), recognized for its extensive and inclusive coverage of scientific literature. The specific search criterion employed were as outlined below:

                              1)

Based on the retrieval rules of WoS platform and definition of nanozymes, the searching terms were set as: TS (topic subject) = ("nanozyme*" OR "nanoenzyme*" OR ("nano*" AND ("*ase-like" OR "*ase-mim*" OR "enzyme mim*" OR "enzyme like"))) AND TS = ("cancer*" OR "tumor*");


                              2)

The types of included documents were confined to "Articles" and "Review Articles";


                              3)

Publications were restricted to those written exclusively in English;


                              4)

Based on the definition of nanozymes, two other rules (below) were used by three independent experienced authors to exclude irrelevant documents;

                                       a.

The documents that were not associated with nanozymes;


                                       b.

The documents that were associated with nanozymes, but not relevant to tumors/cancers.

Our summary of recent studies on nanozyme-based catalytic therapy induced/plus immunotherapy (
                              Table 6
                              ) found that nanozyme-enhanced immunotherapy or nanozyme-mediated immunomodulation was firstly applied in 2019/2020 [309,337,367], and it has developed fast and become a hot spot in the field of nanozymes. The advent of immune checkpoint blockades, now approved for various cancers, has paved the way for combining nanozyme-based catalytic therapies with anti-PD-1, anti-PD-L1 or anti-CTLA-4 treatments, thereby emerging as a prevalent and efficacious therapeutic strategy [90, 249, 273, 368–372]. Similar to CDT, POD-like activity is also the most commonly used activity for nanozymes in the field of immunotherapy. Besides, most nanozymes used in this field are characterized with multi-enzyme-mimicking abilities.
